{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17658708","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17658708"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:54:34+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:54:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20815"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20815","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20815"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13690"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96196"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13690","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13690"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20815"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78916"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"11653"},{"type":"tags","id":"12438"},{"type":"tags","id":"12647"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"32970"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32971"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96196","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/96196"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the pathogenesis of Lyme disease caused by \u003Cem\u003EBorrelia burgdorferi\u003C/em\u003E?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Direct invasion and destruction of joint synovial tissue","Endotoxin-mediated activation of complement cascade","Host immune response to bacterial antigens causing inflammation","Neurotoxin production causing peripheral nerve demyelination","Production of potent exotoxins that directly damage host tissues"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe pathogenesis of Lyme disease is primarily due to the \u003Cstrong\u003Ehost immune response to bacterial antigens causing inflammation\u003C/strong\u003E. \u003Cem\u003EBorrelia burgdorferi\u003C/em\u003E does not produce endotoxins or exotoxins that directly damage host tissues. Instead, the pathology associated with Lyme disease results from the inflammatory response triggered when bacterial lipoproteins bind to Toll-like receptor 2 (TLR2) on macrophages, leading to the release of pro-inflammatory cytokines such as interleukin-6 (IL-6) and tumor necrosis factor (TNF).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProduction of potent exotoxins that directly damage host tissues\u003C/strong\u003E - \u003Cem\u003EB. burgdorferi\u003C/em\u003E does not produce exotoxins that directly damage host tissues.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEndotoxin-mediated activation of complement cascade\u003C/strong\u003E - Unlike gram-negative bacteria, \u003Cem\u003EB. burgdorferi\u003C/em\u003E does not produce endotoxin (lipopolysaccharide).\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDirect invasion and destruction of joint synovial tissue\u003C/strong\u003E - Joint inflammation in Lyme arthritis is primarily immune-mediated rather than due to direct tissue destruction by the bacteria.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENeurotoxin production causing peripheral nerve demyelination\u003C/strong\u003E - \u003Cem\u003EB. burgdorferi\u003C/em\u003E does not produce neurotoxins; neurological manifestations are immune-mediated.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe bacteria evade the host immune response through antigenic variation of its VlsE surface protein. Chronic manifestations of Lyme disease, such as late arthritis, may involve molecular mimicry, where the immune response against bacterial antigens cross-reacts with self antigens, though the specific antigens involved remain unknown.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Borrelia burgdorferi pathology is primarily due to host immune response rather than bacterial toxins.","Initial immune response to Borrelia burgdorferi involves TLR2 activation on macrophages, leading to pro-inflammatory cytokine release.","Borrelia burgdorferi evades antibody-mediated immunity through antigenic variation of its VlsE surface protein.","Chronic manifestations of Lyme disease may involve molecular mimicry between bacterial and self antigens."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 8; pages 378-379."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78916"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20815"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78916","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/78916"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-31T17:10:53+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-31T17:13:40+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13690"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96196"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11653","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11653"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Infectious diseases","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":7,"createdAt":"2025-02-28T18:04:44+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-28T18:04:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"18"}},"heading":{"